    Async ValueTask Pooling in .NET 5
    .NET 5中的异步值任务池

    Stephen Toub - MSFT

    March 16th, 202020 1
    2020年3月16日20 1

    The async/await feature in C# has revolutionized how developers targeting .NET write asynchronous code. Sprinkle some async and await around, change some return types to be tasks, and badda bing badda boom, you’ve got an asynchronous implementation. In theory.
    C#中的async/await特性彻底改变了面向.NET的开发人员编写异步代码的方式。添加一些 async 和 await ，将一些返回类型更改为task，然后badda bing badda boom，你就得到了一个异步实现。理论上

    In practice, obviously I’ve exaggerated the ease with which a codebase can be made fully asynchronous, and as with many a software development task, the devil is often in the details. One such “devil” that performance-minded .NET developers are likely familiar with is the state machine object that enables an async method to perform its magic.
    在实践中，显然我夸大了代码库可以完全异步化的容易性，而且和许多软件开发任务一样，细节往往是魔鬼。注重性能的.NET开发人员可能熟悉的一个这样的“魔鬼”就是状态机对象，它使async方法能够执行它的魔力。

    State Machines and Allocations
    状态机和分配

    When you write an async method in C#, the compiler rewrites that method into a state machine, where the bulk of your code in your async method is moved into a MoveNext method on a compiler-generated type (a struct in Release builds), and with that MoveNext method littered with jumps and labels that enable the method to suspend and resume at await points. An await‘d incomplete tasks has a continuation (a callback) hooked up to it that, upon the task’s eventual completion, calls back to the MoveNext method and jumps to the location where the function was suspended. In order for local variables to maintain their state across these method exits and re-entrances, relevant “locals” are rewritten by the compiler to be fields on the state machine type. And in order for that state machine as a struct to persist across those same suspensions, it needs to be moved to the heap.
    当你在C#中编写异步方法时，编译器会将该方法重写到状态机中，其中异步方法中的大部分代码被移动到编译器生成的类型上的 MoveNext 方法（Release build中的结构），并且 MoveNext 方法中充满了跳转和标签，使该方法能够在 await 点挂起和恢复。 await 'd的未完成任务有一个连接到它的延续（回调），在任务最终完成时，它会回调 MoveNext 方法并跳转到函数被挂起的位置。为了使局部变量在这些方法出口和重新入口之间保持它们的状态，相关的“局部变量”被编译器重写为状态机类型上的字段。为了使状态机作为一个结构体能够在这些相同的挂起之间持久存在，它需要被移动到堆中。

    The C# compiler and the .NET runtime try hard to avoid putting that state machine on the heap. Many async method invocations actually complete synchronously, and the compiler and runtime are tuned to that use case. As noted, in Release builds the state machine generated by the compiler is a struct, and when an async method is invoked, the state machine starts its life on the stack. If the async method completes without ever suspending, the state machine will happily complete having never caused an allocation. However, if the async method ever needs to suspend, the state machine needs to somehow be promoted to the heap.
    C#编译器和.NET运行时尽量避免将状态机放在堆上。许多异步方法调用实际上是同步完成的，编译器和运行时都是针对该用例进行调优的。如前所述，在Release构建中，编译器生成的状态机是一个struct，当调用异步方法时，状态机在堆栈上开始其生命周期。如果async方法在没有挂起的情况下完成，状态机将很高兴地完成，而不会导致分配。但是，如果async方法需要挂起，状态机需要以某种方式提升到堆。

    In .NET Framework, the moment a Task– or ValueTask-returning async method (both generic and non-generic) suspends for the first time, several allocations occur:
    在.NET Framework中，当 Task 或 ValueTask 返回异步方法（包括泛型和非泛型）首次挂起时，会发生几个分配：

    1. The state machine struct is copied to the heap via standard runtime boxing; every state machine implements the IAsyncStateMachine interface, and the runtime literally casts the struct to this interface, resulting in an allocation.
      状态机结构通过标准运行时装箱复制到堆中;每个状态机都实现 IAsyncStateMachine 接口，运行时将结构体直接转换为该接口，从而产生分配。

    2. The runtime captures the current ExecutionContext, and then allocates an object (it calls this a “runner”) that it uses to store both the boxed state machine and the ExecutionContext (note, too, that in the .NET Framework, capturing ExecutionContext when it’s not the default also results in one or more allocations).
      运行时捕获当前的 ExecutionContext ，然后分配一个对象（它称之为“runner”），用于存储盒装状态机和 ExecutionContext （还要注意，在.NET Framework中，捕获 ExecutionContext 时不是默认值也会导致一个或多个分配）。

    3. The runtime allocates an Action delegate that points to a method on that runner object, because the awaiter pattern requires an Action that can be passed to the awaiter’s {Unsafe}OnCompleted method; when invoked, the Action will use the captured ExecutionContext to invoke the MoveNext method on the state machine.
      运行时分配一个指向运行器对象上的方法的 Action 委托，因为waiter模式需要一个可以传递给waiter的 {Unsafe}OnCompleted 方法的 Action ;调用时， Action 将使用捕获的 ExecutionContext 调用状态机上的 MoveNext 方法。

    4. The runtime allocates a Task object that will be completed when the async method completes and that’s returned from the async method to its synchronous caller (if the async method is typed to return a ValueTask, the ValueTask struct is just wrapped around the Task object).
      运行时分配一个 Task 对象，当异步方法完成时，该对象将被完成，并从异步方法返回给同步调用者（如果异步方法被键入为返回 ValueTask ，则 ValueTask 结构体将被封装在 Task 对象周围）。

    That’s at least four allocations when an async method suspends for the first time. On top of that, every subsequent time the async method suspends, if we find ourselves with a non-default ExecutionContext (e.g. it’s carrying state for an AsyncLocal<T>), the runtime re-allocates that runner object and then re-allocates the Action that points to it (because delegates are immutable), for at least two additional allocations each time the async method suspends after the first time. Here’s a simple repro of that in Visual Studio, with the right window showing allocations as profiled by the .NET Object Allocation Tracking tool:
    当异步方法第一次挂起时，至少有四次分配。最重要的是，每次后续的async方法挂起时，如果我们发现自己有一个非默认的 ExecutionContext （例如：它携带 AsyncLocal<T> 的状态），运行时重新分配该runner对象，然后重新分配指向它的 Action （因为委托是不可变的），每次异步方法在第一次之后挂起时至少需要两次额外分配。下面是Visual Studio中的一个简单再现，右侧窗口显示了.NET对象分配跟踪工具分析的分配：

    This has been improved significantly for .NET Core, in particular as of .NET Core 2.1. When an async method suspends, a Task is allocated. But it’s not of the base Task or Task<TResult> type. Instead, it’s of an internal AsyncStateMachineBox<TStateMachine> type that derives from Task. The state machine struct is stored in a strongly-typed field on this derived type, eliminating the need for a separate boxing allocation. This type also has a field for the captured ExecutionContext (which is immutable in .NET Core, which means capturing one never allocates), which means we don’t need a separate runner object. And the runtime now has special code paths that support passing this AsyncStateMachineBox<TStateMachine> type directly through to all awaiters the runtime knows about, which means that as long as an async method only ever awaits Task, Task<TResult>, ValueTask, or ValueTask<TResult> (either directly or via their ConfigureAwait counterparts), it needn’t allocate an Action delegate at all. Then, since we have direct access to the ExecutionContext field, subsequent suspensions don’t require allocating a new runner (runners are gone entirely), which also means even if we did need to allocate an Action, we don’t need to re-allocate it. That means, whereas in .NET Framework we have at least four allocations for the first suspension and often at least two allocations for each subsequent suspension, in .NET Core we have one allocation for the first suspension (worst case two, if custom awaiters are used), and that’s it. Other changes, such as a rewrite to the ThreadPool‘s queueing infrastructure, also significantly decreased allocations.
    这对于.NET Core有了显著改进，特别是从.NET Core 2.1开始。当异步方法挂起时，分配 Task 。但它不是基础 Task 或 Task<TResult> 类型。相反，它是从 Task 派生的内部 AsyncStateMachineBox<TStateMachine> 类型。状态机结构存储在此派生类型的强类型字段中，从而消除了单独装箱分配的需要。该类型也有一个捕获的 ExecutionContext 字段（在.NET Core中是不可变的，这意味着捕获的一个永远不会分配），这意味着我们不需要单独的runner对象。运行时现在有了特殊的代码路径，支持将这个 AsyncStateMachineBox<TStateMachine> 类型直接传递给运行时知道的所有等待者，这意味着只要异步方法只等待 Task 、 Task<TResult> 、 ValueTask 或 ValueTask<TResult> （直接或通过它们的 ConfigureAwait 对应物），它根本不需要分配 Action 委托。 然后，由于我们可以直接访问 ExecutionContext 字段，后续暂停不需要分配新的runner（runner完全消失），这也意味着即使我们确实需要分配 Action ，我们也不需要重新分配它。这意味着，在.NET Framework中，我们至少有四个分配用于第一次挂起，通常每个后续挂起至少有两个分配用于第一次挂起，在.NET Core中，我们有一个分配用于第一次挂起（最坏情况下，两个，如果使用自定义等待器），仅此而已。其他改变，例如重写 ThreadPool 的排队基础设施，也显著减少了分配。

    That change has had a very measurable impact on performance (and, as it happens, on more than just performance; it’s also very beneficial for debugging), and we can all rejoice in seeing unnecessary allocations removed. However, as noted, one allocation still remains when an async method completes asynchronously. But… what if we could get rid of that last one, too? What if we could make it so that invoking an async method had (amortized) zero-allocation overhead, regardless of whether it completed synchronously or asynchronously?
    这一变化对业绩产生了非常可衡量的影响（而且，碰巧的是，不仅仅是业绩;这对于调试也非常有益），我们都可以为看到不必要的分配被删除而感到高兴。然而，如上所述，当异步方法异步完成时，仍然保留一个分配。但如果我们能把最后一个也去掉呢如果我们能够使调用一个async方法的开销（摊销）为零，而不管它是同步还是异步完成的呢？

    ValueTask

    ValueTask<TResult> was introduced in the .NET Core 1.0 timeframe to help developers avoid allocations when async methods complete synchronously. It was a relatively simple struct representing a discriminated union between a TResult and a Task<TResult>. When used as the result type of an async method, if an invocation of the async method returns synchronously, regardless of the value of the TResult result, the method incurs zero allocations of overhead: the state machine doesn’t need to be moved to the heap, and no Task<TResult> need be allocated for the result; the result value is simply stored into the TResult field of the returned ValueTask<TResult>. However, if the async method completes asynchronously, the runtime falls back to behaving just as it would with Task<TResult>: it produces the single AsyncStateMachineBox<TStateMachine> task, which is then wrapped in the returned ValueTask<TResult> struct.
    ValueTask<TResult> 是在.NET Core 1.0框架中引入的，以帮助开发人员在异步方法同步完成时避免分配。它是一个相对简单的结构体，代表了 TResult 和 Task<TResult> 之间的区别并集。当用作异步方法的结果类型时，如果异步方法的调用同步返回，不管 TResult 结果的值如何，该方法的开销分配为零：状态机不需要移动到堆中，也不需要为结果分配 Task<TResult> ;结果值被简单地存储到返回的 ValueTask<TResult> 的 TResult 字段中。但是，如果异步方法异步完成，运行时福尔斯与 Task<TResult> 一样的行为：它生成单个 AsyncStateMachineBox<TStateMachine> 任务，然后将其包装在返回的 ValueTask<TResult> 结构中。

    In .NET Core 2.1, we introduced the IValueTaskSource<TResult> interface, along with non-generic counterparts ValueTask and IValueTaskSource. We also made ValueTask<TResult> capable of storing not just a TResult and a Task<TResult>, but also an IValueTaskSource<TResult> (same for the non-generic ValueTask, which could store a Task or an IValueTaskSource). This advanced interface allows an enterprising developer to write their own backing store for the value task, and they can do so in a way that allows them to reuse that backing store object for multiple non-concurrent operations (much more information on this is available in this blog post. For example, an individual Socket is generally used for no more than one receive operation and one send operation at a time. Socket was modified to store a reusable/resettable IValueTaskSource<int> for each direction, and each consecutive read or write operation that completes asynchronously hands out a ValueTask<int> backed by the appropriate shared instance. This means that in the vast majority of cases, the ValueTask<int>-based ReceiveAsync/SendAsync methods on Socket end up being non-allocating, regardless of whether they complete synchronously or asynchronously. A handful of types got this treatment, but only where we knew it would be impactful because the types were often used on high-throughput code paths, we knew we could do it in a way where it would pretty much always be a win (often performance optimizations come with trade-offs), and we knew it would be worth the painstaking effort it would take to effectively implement these interfaces.
    在.NET Core 2.1中，我们引入了 IValueTaskSource<TResult> 接口，沿着非通用接口 ValueTask 和 IValueTaskSource 。我们还使 ValueTask<TResult> 不仅能够存储 TResult 和 Task<TResult> ，还能够存储 IValueTaskSource<TResult> （非通用的 ValueTask 也可以存储 Task 或 IValueTaskSource ）。这个高级接口允许有进取心的开发人员为值任务编写他们自己的后备存储，并且他们可以以允许他们重用后备存储对象进行多个非并发操作的方式来这样做（关于这方面的更多信息可以在这篇博客文章中获得。例如，单个 Socket 通常一次用于不超过一个接收操作和一个发送操作。 Socket 被修改为为每个方向存储可重用/可重置的 IValueTaskSource<int> ，并且异步完成的每个连续读或写操作输出由适当的共享实例支持的 ValueTask<int> 。 这意味着在绝大多数情况下， Socket 上基于 ValueTask<int> 的 ReceiveAsync / SendAsync 方法最终都是非分配的，不管它们是同步还是异步完成的。少数类型得到了这种处理，但只有在我们知道它会有影响力的情况下，因为这些类型经常被用在高吞吐量的代码路径上，我们知道我们可以以一种几乎总是胜利的方式来做到这一点（通常性能优化是有权衡的），并且我们知道有效地实现这些接口所付出的艰苦努力是值得的。

    As such, a handful of implementations were added in .NET Core 2.1 in key areas, like System.Net.Sockets, System.Threading.Channels, and System.IO.Pipelines, but not much beyond that. We subsequently introduced the ManualResetValueTaskSource<TResult> type to make such implementations easier, and as a result more implementations of these interfaces were added in .NET Core 3.0 and also in .NET 5, though mostly as internal implementation details within various components, like System.Net.Http.
    因此，在.NET Core 2.1中添加了一些关键领域的实现，如 System.Net.Sockets 、 System.Threading.Channels 和 System.IO.Pipelines ，但除此之外没有太多。我们随后引入了 ManualResetValueTaskSource<TResult> 类型，以使这样的实现更容易，因此，在.NET Core 3.0和.NET 5中添加了更多这些接口的实现，尽管大多数是作为各种组件中的内部实现细节，如 System.Net.Http 。

    .NET 5 Improvements .NET 5改进

    In .NET 5, we’re experimenting with taking this optimization much further. With .NET 5 Preview 1, if prior to your process running you set the DOTNET_SYSTEM_THREADING_POOLASYNCVALUETASKS environment variable to either true or 1, the runtime will use state machine box objects that implement the IValueTaskSource and IValueTaskSource<TResult> interfaces, and it will pool the objects it creates to back the instances returned from async ValueTask or async ValueTask<TResult> methods. So, if as in the earlier example you repeatedly invoke the same method and await its result, each time you’ll end up getting back a ValueTask that, under the covers, is wrapping the exact same object, simply reset each time to enable it to track another execution. Magic.
    在.NET 5中，我们正在试验进一步进行这种优化。在.NET 5 Preview 1中，如果在进程运行之前将 DOTNET_SYSTEM_THREADING_POOLASYNCVALUETASKS 环境变量设置为 true 或 1 ，则运行时将使用实现 IValueTaskSource 和 IValueTaskSource<TResult> 接口的状态机框对象，并将其创建的对象池化以支持从 async ValueTask 或 async ValueTask<TResult> 方法返回的实例。所以，如果像前面的例子一样，你重复调用相同的方法并等待它的结果，每次你最终都会得到一个 ValueTask ，在掩盖之下，包装完全相同的对象，只需重置每次，使它能够跟踪另一个执行。魔法

    Why isn’t it just on by default right now? Two main reasons:
    为什么现在不默认开启呢？两个主要原因：

    1. Pooling isn’t free. There are a variety of ways allocations can be eliminated by a developer looking to optimize their code. One is to simply improve the code to no longer need the allocation; from a performance perspective, this is generally very low risk. Another is to reuse an existing object already readily available, such as by adding an additional field to some existing object with a similar lifespan; this likely requires more performance analysis, but is still often a clear win. Then comes pooling. Pooling can be very beneficial when it’s really expensive to construct the thing being pooled; a good example of this is with HTTPS connection pooling, where the cost of establishing a new secure connection is generally orders of magnitude more expensive than accessing one in even the most naïve of pooling data structures. The more controversial form of pooling is when the pool is for cheaply constructed objects, with the goal of avoiding garbage collection costs. In employing such a pool, the developer is betting that they can implement a custom allocator (which is really what a pool is) that’s better than the general-purpose GC allocator. Beating the GC is not trivial. But, a developer might be able to, given knowledge they have of their specific scenario. For example, the .NET GC is very good at efficiently collecting short-lived objects, those that become collectible in generation 0, and attempting to pool such objects can easily make a program more expensive (even if doing so looks good on a microbenchmark focused on measuring allocation). But if you know that your objects are likely to survive gen0, such as if they’re used to represent potentially long-latency asynchronous operations, it’s possible a custom pool could shave off some overhead. We haven’t made this async ValueTask pooling the default yet because, while it looks good on microbenchmarks, we’re not sure it’s actually a meaningful improvement on real-world workloads.
      共享不是免费的。开发人员希望优化他们的代码，可以通过多种方式消除分配。一种是简单地改进代码，使其不再需要分配;从性能的角度来看，这通常是非常低的风险。另一种方法是重用已经很容易获得的现有对象，例如通过向具有相似寿命的某个现有对象添加附加字段;这可能需要更多的性能分析，但通常仍然是明显的胜利。然后是池。当构建被池化的东西非常昂贵时，池化是非常有益的;一个很好的例子是HTTPS连接池，其中建立新的安全连接的成本通常比访问即使是最简单的池化数据结构中的一个高数量级。更有争议的池化形式是池用于廉价构造的对象，目的是避免垃圾收集成本。 在使用这样的池时，开发人员打赌他们可以实现一个比通用GC分配器更好的自定义分配器（这就是池的真正含义）。打败GC不是小事。但是，开发人员可能能够，考虑到他们对特定场景的了解。例如，.NET GC非常擅长有效地收集短期对象，即那些在第0代中可收集的对象，并且试图将这些对象汇集起来很容易使程序变得更昂贵（即使这样做在专注于测量分配的微基准上看起来很好）。但是，如果您知道您的对象很可能在gen0中幸存下来，例如如果它们被用来表示潜在的长延迟异步操作，那么自定义池可能会减少一些开销。我们还没有将这个 async ValueTask 池设置为默认值，因为虽然它在微基准测试中看起来不错，但我们不确定它是否真的对现实工作负载有意义的改进。

    2. ValueTasks have constraints. The Task and Task<TResult> types were designed to be very robust. You can cache them. You can await them any number of times. They support multiple continuations. They’re thread-safe, with any number of threads able to concurrently register continuations. And in addition to being awaitable and supporting asynchronous completion notifications, they also support a blocking model, with synchronous callers able to wait for a result to be available. None of that holds for ValueTask and ValueTask<TResult>. Because they might be backed by resettable IValueTaskSource instances, you mustn’t cache them (the thing they wrap might get reused) nor await them multiple times. You mustn’t try to register multiple continuations (after the first completes the object might try to reset itself for another operation), whether concurrently or not. And you mustn’t try to block waiting for them to complete (IValueTaskSource implementations need not provide such semantics). As long as callers directly await the result of calling a method that returns a ValueTask or ValueTask<TResult>, everything should work well, but the moment someone steps off that golden path, things can go awry quickly; that could mean getting exceptions, or it could mean corruption in the process. Further, these complications generally only present themselves when the ValueTask or ValueTask<TResult> wraps an IValueTaskSource implementation; when they wrap a Task, things typically “just work”, as the ValueTask inherits Task‘s robustness, and when they wrap a raw result value, the constraints technically don’t apply at all. And that means that by switching async ValueTask methods from being backed by Tasks as they are today to instead being backed by these pooled IValueTaskSource implementations, we could be exposing latent bugs in a developer’s app, either directly or via libraries they consume. An upcoming release of the Roslyn Analyzers will include an analyzer that should help find most misuse.
      ValueTasks有约束。 Task 和 Task<TResult> 类型设计为非常耐用。你可以缓存它们。你可以等待他们任何次数。它们支持多个延续。它们是线程安全的，任何数量的线程都可以并发注册延续。除了可等待和支持异步完成通知之外，它们还支持阻塞模型，同步调用方能够等待结果可用。这一切都不适用于 ValueTask 和 ValueTask<TResult> 。因为它们可能由可重置的 IValueTaskSource 实例支持，所以您不能缓存它们（它们包装的东西可能会被重用），也不能多次等待它们。无论是否并发，都不能尝试注册多个continuation（在第一个完成之后，对象可能会尝试重置自身以进行另一个操作）。而且你不能试图阻塞等待它们完成（ IValueTaskSource 实现不需要提供这样的语义）。 只要调用者直接等待调用返回 ValueTask 或 ValueTask<TResult> 的方法的结果，一切都应该工作得很好，但是一旦有人离开了黄金路径，事情就会很快出错;这可能意味着获得例外，也可能意味着过程中的腐败。此外，这些复杂性通常仅在 ValueTask 或 ValueTask<TResult> 包装 IValueTaskSource 实现时出现;当它们包装一个 Task 时，事情通常“正常工作”，因为 ValueTask 继承了 Task 的健壮性，而当它们包装一个原始结果值时，约束在技术上根本不适用。这意味着，通过将 async ValueTask 方法从今天的 Task 方法支持到由这些池化的 IValueTaskSource 实现支持，我们可能会暴露开发者应用中的潜在bug，无论是直接还是通过他们使用的库。即将发布的Roslyn分析仪将包括一个分析仪，应该有助于发现大多数误用。

    Call to Action 行动呼吁

    This is where you come in. If you have an application you think would benefit from this pooling, we’d love to hear from you. Download .NET 5 Preview 1. Try turning on the feature. Does anything break, and if so, in your code, or in another library, or in .NET itself? And do you see measurable performance wins, whether measured as throughput or latency or working set or anything else of interest? Note that the change only affects async ValueTask and async ValueTask<TResult> methods, so if you have async Task or async Task<TResult> methods, you might also need to experiment with first changing those to use their ValueTask equivalents.
    这就是你要来的地方。如果您有一个应用程序，您认为将受益于此池，我们很乐意听取您的意见。下载.NET 5预览版1.尝试打开功能。是否有任何东西损坏，如果是，在您的代码中，或在另一个库中，或在.NET本身中？您是否看到了可衡量的性能胜利，无论是通过吞吐量、延迟、工作集还是其他感兴趣的东西来衡量？请注意，此更改仅影响 async ValueTask 和 async ValueTask<TResult> 方法，因此如果您有 async Task 或 async Task<TResult> 方法，您可能还需要尝试先更改这些方法以使用它们的 ValueTask 等效方法。

    Issue dotnet/runtime#13633 is tracking our figuring out what we should do with this feature for .NET 5, and we’d love to hear from you; we’d welcome you posting any thoughts or results there.
    Issue dotnet/runtime#13633正在跟踪我们的研究如何使用.NET 5的这个特性，我们很乐意听到你的消息;我们欢迎你在那里发表任何想法或结果。

    Thanks in advance for any feedback, and happy pooling!
    提前感谢任何反馈，和快乐的池！

      • Stephen Toub March 17, 2020 3:36 pm 0
        Stephen Toub三月17，2020 3：36下午0

        Thanks, glad you liked it.
        谢谢，很高兴你喜欢。

        There’s a ton of potential benefit to ValueTask, and in particular ValueTask<T>. Consider a method like Stream.ReadAsync, which very frequently will complete synchronously, whether on a type like MemoryStream where every read completes synchronously, or a type like FileStream or BufferedStream where most reads complete synchronously because of an internal buffer, or a type like DeflateStream or CryptoStream which will complete synchronously if the underlying stream does, or a type like NetworkStream which will complete synchronously if the kernel has data already available for the connection. In such cases, these methods can be called on very hot paths, and avoiding allocating an object each time can definitely be measurable.
        ValueTask 有很多潜在的好处，尤其是 ValueTask<T> 。考虑类似 Stream.ReadAsync 的方法，其将非常频繁地同步完成，无论是在类似 MemoryStream 的类型上，其中每个读取同步完成，还是在类似 FileStream 或 BufferedStream 的类型上，其中大多数读取由于内部缓冲器而同步完成，或者在类似 DeflateStream 或 CryptoStream 的类型上，如果底层流完成，则将同步完成，或者像 NetworkStream 这样的类型，如果内核已经有可用于连接的数据，它将同步完成。在这种情况下，这些方法可以在非常热的路径上调用，并且避免每次分配对象绝对是可以测量的。

        But even for asynchronous completion, the benefit can be very measurable when these things show up on hot paths. With the IValueTaskSource support, we’ve for example made it so that Socket.SendAsync/ReceiveAsync are generally allocation-free, regardless of whether they complete synchronously or asynchronously, as long as you’re using the newer overloads that return ValueTask<T>. You can see the impact of that with a little demo like this:
        但即使是异步完成，当这些东西出现在热路径上时，好处也是非常可衡量的。例如，通过 IValueTaskSource 支持，我们已经使 Socket.SendAsync / ReceiveAsync 通常是无分配的，无论它们是同步还是异步完成，只要您使用返回 ValueTask<T> 的较新重载。你可以通过下面的一个小演示来看到它的影响：

        
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Net;
using System.Net.Sockets;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

class Program
{
    static async Task Main()
    {
        Console.WriteLine(Path.GetFileName(Path.GetDirectoryName(typeof(object).Assembly.Location)));

        var listener = new Socket(AddressFamily.InterNetwork, SocketType.Stream, ProtocolType.Tcp);
        var client = new Socket(AddressFamily.InterNetwork, SocketType.Stream, ProtocolType.Tcp);
        listener.Bind(new IPEndPoint(IPAddress.Loopback, 0));
        listener.Listen(1);
        client.Connect(listener.LocalEndPoint);

        var server = listener.Accept();
        long count = 0;

        _ = Task.Run(() =>
        {
            AppDomain.MonitoringIsEnabled = true;
            Thread.Sleep(1000);
            while (true)
            {
                long memBefore = AppDomain.CurrentDomain.MonitoringTotalAllocatedMemorySize;
                long iterBefore = Volatile.Read(ref count);
                Thread.Sleep(1000);
                long iterAfter = Volatile.Read(ref count);
                long memAfter = AppDomain.CurrentDomain.MonitoringTotalAllocatedMemorySize;
                Console.WriteLine($"Iterations: {iterAfter - iterBefore:N0}, Bytes: {memAfter - memBefore:N0}");
            }
        });

        var buffer = new ArraySegment<byte>(new byte[1]); // ### 1
        // var buffer = new Memory<byte>(new byte[1]);       // ### 2

        while (true)
        {
            var r = client.ReceiveAsync(buffer, SocketFlags.None);
            await server.SendAsync(buffer, SocketFlags.None);
            await r;
            count++;
        }
    }
}

        When I run this with the ### 1 line, I get values like:
        当我用 ### 1 行运行此命令时，我得到的值如下：

        Iterations: 44,317, Bytes: 3,565,944
        迭代次数：44，317，字节：3,565,944

        whereas when I run it with the ### 2 line, I get values like:
        而当我用 ### 2 行运行它时，我得到的值如下：

        Iterations: 49,798, Bytes: 0
        迭代次数：49，798，字节：0

        so both a throughput improvement and a complete elimination of the allocation overhead. This is also a serialized test, but such allocation reduction has a way of magnifying other improvements on loaded servers.
        因此吞吐量的提高和分配开销的完全消除。这也是一个序列化的测试，但是这样的分配减少有一种放大加载服务器上的其他改进的方式。

        We know it’s valuable for cases like that. My comment in this post about microbenchmarks was more about this automatic implementation behind async methods, and as for real-world impact, that’s the point of my asking for folks to try it out
        我们知道它对这种案子很有价值。我在这篇文章中关于微基准测试的评论更多地是关于异步方法背后的自动实现，至于现实世界的影响，这就是我要求人们尝试它的意义

        Will there ever be a point in .NET where ValueTask is preferred over Task always
        在.NET中是否会有一个点，ValueTask总是比Task更受欢迎

        Always? From my perspective, no.
        一直都是吗从我的角度来看，没有。
        https://devblogs.microsoft.com/dotnet/understanding-the-whys-whats-and-whens-of-valuetask/.

        Is it, in theory, possible for ValueTask to completely mitigate the “dont await twice” problem, ever?
        从理论上讲，ValueTask有可能完全缓解“不要等待两次”的问题吗？

        If you’re ok allocating, sure. But if the struct is going to wrap a reusable/shared object, then there will always be the possibility for a copy of that struct to refer to the object after it’s already being used by someone else.
        如果你能分配的话，当然可以。但是如果结构要包装一个可重用/共享对象，那么在对象已经被其他人使用之后，该结构的副本总是有可能引用该对象。

        will Task APIs (e.g. Task.WhenAll, Task.WhenAny etc) will ever be amended to accept ValueTasks as well?
        将任务API（例如任务.WhenAll，Task.WhenAny等）也会被修改为接受ValueTasks？

        WhenAny: no. WhenAny needs to hook up a continuation to the task, so if you’re only allowed to do that once, you’ve invalidated every value task other than the one that completes first.
        WhenAny：否。WhenAny需要连接到任务的续篇，所以如果只允许您这样做一次，则除了最先完成的任务之外，您已经使每个有价值的任务无效。

        WhenAll: maybe. It’s possible to implement it; I don’t know whether we’d choose to. https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/23625

      Hello Stephen, 你好斯蒂芬，
      as always, thanks for the great article.
      一如既往，谢谢你的伟大文章。

      I am sure that many applications will benefit from the scenario enabled by the “DOTNET_SYSTEM_THREADING_POOLASYNCVALUETASKS” switch.
      我确信许多应用程序将受益于由“DOTNET_SYSTEM_THREADING_POOLASYNCVALUETASKS”开关启用的场景。
      We have TLS 1.3 implementation for many .NET platforms (Compact .Net Framework, .Net 2.0+, MONO, .Net Standard 1.5+ etc.). If you are curious, we have developed own Task-like infrastructure for old platforms. I am using custom awaiters in the custom dataflow that processes TLS records. As mentioned in the article, own awaiter for the Socket Send/Receive operations should be very beneficial for all applications.
      我们为许多.NET平台提供TLS 1.3实现（Compact .Net Framework，.Net 2.0+，MONO，.Net Standard 1.5+等）。如果您好奇，我们已经为旧平台开发了自己的类似Task的基础设施。我在处理TLS记录的自定义数据流中使用自定义等待器。正如本文中所提到的，自己的套接字发送/接收操作的等待器对所有应用程序都非常有益。
      I am sure that Socket operations are not rare exceptions. Custom awaiters, ValueTask, IValueTaskSource and similar constructs are great extensions of the “classic” Task-based asynchrony.
      我确信Socket操作不是罕见的异常。自定义等待器、ValueTask、IValueTaskSource和类似的结构是“经典”基于任务的异步的伟大扩展。

      E.g. every stage in our custom dataflow is backed by its own instance of the (I)AsyncProducerConsumerCollection. Recently I have replaced task-based “consumer” methods by the custom awaiter pattern. As you can probably imagine, an instance of the collection is an awaiter. This change eliminated the allocation of many unneeded Tasks.
      例如，我们的自定义数据流中的每个阶段都由其自己的（I）AsyncProducerConsumerCollection实例支持。最近，我用定制的waiter模式取代了基于任务的“消费者”方法。正如您可能想象的那样，集合的实例是一个awater。这一变化消除了许多不需要的任务的分配。

      The description of the class reveals the main weakness that is mentioned in your article as well. The programming model with such optimized constructs becomes tricky and is very unintuitive for inexperienced developers.
      类的描述也揭示了您文章中提到的主要弱点。具有这种优化结构的编程模型变得棘手，对于没有经验的开发人员来说非常不直观。

      /// <summary>
      /// Consumer side of the ManyProducersSingleConsumerCollection offers implementation of the awaiter pattern. Special implementation of the awaiter pattern helps to get rid of many unneeded instances of the <see cref="Task{TResult}"/>.
      /// As the name of the class suggests, this class is suitable for (one or many) producer(s) - ONE consumer scenario.
      /// Only ONE client can call ONE of the TakeAsyncOneConsumer/TakeAsync methods at the same time and await the result.
      /// Multiple simultaneous calls of the TakeAsyncOneConsumer/TakeAsync methods lead to the undefined behavior - usually unexpected exception or a hard to find deadlock.
      /// As a rule of thumb and especially if you are not sure what the previous sentence means for your solution, use the <see cref="SimpleAsyncProducerConsumerCollection{TItem}"/> instead.
      /// </summary>
